I. DECLARED PURPOSE

This document defines the complete operational architecture of the Book Extraction Machine (BEM).

The Book Extraction Machine is a layered synthesis protocol designed to convert unstructured textual material into formal, transferable structural knowledge.

This is not summarization.

This is structural extraction.

The objective is:

Preserve original signal.

Remove narrative noise.

Isolate irreducible structural units.

Encode them uniformly.

Enable cross-domain transfer.

Preserve falsifiability.

The canonical irreducible extraction unit is:

Primitive

This term is locked and non-negotiable.

II. CORE PHILOSOPHY

No compression without structural mapping.

No abstraction without anchor.

No model without break condition.

No interpretation without perceptual separation.

No synthesis without transfer mapping.

Extraction is not interpretation.

Extraction precedes synthesis.

III. LAYERED SYNTHESIS PIPELINE

The extraction pipeline is strictly layered.

No layer may be skipped.

No layer may be merged informally.

Pipeline:

Signal → Kernel → Primitive → Structure Map → Transfer Map

IV. LAYER DEFINITIONS
1. SIGNAL

Definition:
Raw textual material directly from source.

Includes:

Author claims

Examples

Mechanisms

Data

Case studies

Analogies

Rules:

Signal may be quoted.

“VERBATIM” label is only used when exact source text is provided.

Signal cannot be paraphrased and labeled verbatim.

Signal is noisy.
Signal contains redundancy.
Signal contains rhetoric.

Signal is not yet structural.

2. KERNEL

Definition:
Mechanism distilled from signal without narrative language.

Kernel expresses:

Causal claim

Structural rule

Conditional logic

Incentive relationship

Constraint mechanism

Kernel format:

KERNEL:
If X condition,
Then Y mechanism,
Because Z structural reason.

Kernel must:

Remove adjectives.

Remove persuasion.

Remove metaphor.

Preserve logic.

Preserve falsifiability.

Kernel is testable.
Kernel must contain a break condition.

Break Condition Template:
This kernel fails if:

A counterexample exists where X occurs but Y does not follow.

Or if Z is demonstrably false.

No kernel may be stored without break conditions.

3. PRIMITIVE (CANONICAL IRREDUCIBLE UNIT)

Definition:
A Primitive is the smallest structurally independent, falsifiable rule extracted from text.

A Primitive:

Cannot be subdivided without loss of logic.

Contains one structural mechanism only.

Contains explicit conditions.

Contains break conditions.

Contains perceptual and formal separation.

Primitive Schema (MANDATORY UNIFORM FORMAT):

PRIMITIVE_ID:
Source:
Chapter:
Signal Reference:
Domain:
Layer Tag:

FORMAL_STATEMENT:
(Strict logical statement of mechanism.)

CONDITIONS:
(List explicit required conditions.)

MECHANISM:
(Explain structural causation concisely.)

BREAK_CONDITIONS:
(Explicit falsification scenarios.)

FAILURE_MODES:
(Common misapplications.)

TRANSFER_CANDIDATES:
(Potential cross-domain mappings.)

CONFIDENCE_LEVEL:
(Low / Medium / High, based on evidence strength.)

Perceptual Section (Separate Block):

PERCEPTUAL_SIGNATURE:
(How it “feels” in live system observation.)

OBSERVABLE_INDICATORS:
(Concrete measurable cues.)

WARNING_FLAGS:
(Signs of misclassification.)

Formal and perceptual blocks must remain separate.

Never blend them.

4. STRUCTURE MAP

Definition:
Graph of Primitives and their relationships.

Structure Map identifies:

Reinforcing primitives.

Balancing primitives.

Preconditions between primitives.

Dependency chains.

Collapse triggers.

Structure Map Output Requirements:

Directed connections.

Edge type classification (causal / amplifying / constraining).

No narrative explanation.

Pure structural mapping.

Structure Map must not invent primitives.

It may only use extracted primitives.

5. TRANSFER MAP

Definition:
Cross-domain applicability testing.

Each Primitive must undergo transfer interrogation.

Transfer Map Template:

ORIGINAL_DOMAIN:
TARGET_DOMAIN:
Structural Equivalent:
Adjustment Required:
Failure Risk:

Transfer only allowed if:

Mechanism remains intact.

Incentive gradients are analogous.

Constraints are comparable.

Transfer must include new break conditions.

No universalization allowed.

V. UNIFORM DATA ENCODING STANDARD

All primitives must follow exact formatting.

No stylistic variation allowed.

No synonym substitution for structural headers.

All caps for schema headers.

Colon after header.

Single blank line separation between schema sections.

This ensures:

Machine readability.

Version tracking.

Schema stability.

Tool compatibility.

VI. SCIENTIFIC RIGOR REQUIREMENTS

Every extraction must include:

Explicit assumptions.

Explicit break conditions.

Explicit counterexample search.

Probability estimate if empirical claim.

Scope boundaries.

No structural claim may be universal unless proven.

All primitives are provisional.

Revision protocol:

If contradiction found:

Log.

Amend primitive.

Version increment.

Preserve old version in archive.

No silent edits.

VII. BREAK CONDITION DOCTRINE

Break Conditions are not negative framing.

Break Conditions define epistemic boundary.

Break Conditions must include:

Condition failure.

Mechanism inversion.

External override scenario.

If Break Conditions are absent:

Primitive is invalid.

VIII. FAILURE MODES OF EXTRACTION

Narrative Contamination:
Injecting author's rhetoric into kernel.

Overcompression:
Merging multiple mechanisms into one primitive.

Premature Synthesis:
Building framework before primitive stability.

Domain Drift:
Assuming cross-domain validity without transfer mapping.

Ego Inflation:
Treating extraction as intellectual performance.

Tool Contamination:
Allowing formatting tools to alter schema structure.

